# Time Complexity

## Brute Force

There are approximately (9 \times 10^{n-1}) n-digit numbers. Computing the digit sum of each number takes (O(n)).

* **Time Complexity:** (O(9 \times 10^{,n-1} \times n)) (exponential in `n`)
* **Space Complexity:** (O(1))

---

## Optimal (Dynamic Programming)

There are:

* `n` digit positions,

* `sum + 1` possible sums,

* `10` possible digits for each transition (constant factor).

* **Time Complexity:** (O(n \times \text{sum})) (more precisely (O(n \times \text{sum} \times 10)), and 10 is constant)

* **Space Complexity:** (O(n \times \text{sum}))

This matches the expected complexity.
